metadata.name: M-tore #1
metadata.description: This token generates abstract art using a recursive algorithm for rectangle splitting. The number of rectangles can be anywhere from 32 to 16384. There are several different strategies for splitting, each one producing distinctive results. The background can be dark or light. Color palettes are generated programmatically in eight different ways (e.g. monochromatic, complementary, analogous, etc.). Textures and effects are also generated programmatically using Perlin noise and pixel manipulation. To add dynamics, there is a probability of having some uncertainty in drawing rectangles, dots, and lines.

metadata.name: night fall moon #35
metadata.description:
it all starts with circles and squares. (but that’s hidden behind flashing lights.)

it gets pulled over and down and then over piece by piece, haphazardly so, and then possibly pulled down again. (but not always.)

it can take a while to process. (like a lot of things.)

it can feel like falling. (possibly, spinning.)

seeing it all can take focus. (but sometimes an impression is all you need.)

you can process it more if you like. (but eventually you’ll be left with nothing.)

[ in “live view” you can press: ]
[ P : process more/pause processing ]
[ S or 1 : save 3000x3000 png ]
[ 2 : save 6000x6000 png ]
[ 3 : save 12000x12000 png ]

metadata.name: Emergence #17
metadata.description:
Using different noise techniques this work is an exploration of the emergence of complex and organic structures from seemingly random noise. The resemblance to ferrofluids and organic "cells" leads to interesting and almost hypnotic visual effects that evolve indefinitely.

Black and white is the most common feature but there are 5 more colour palettes possible. The parameters are hand picked and selected randomly from a pool, every drop is unique.

Press,
"s" to save a screenshot in 4k
"p" to switch to black and white
"space" to pause
"left arrow" to step back
"right arrow" to step forward

Original artwork by William Watkins · Lyon, 2022

metadata.name: (kinder)Garden, Monuments #11
metadata.description:
When Yazid and Zancan started their fxcollab journey, they knew very little about each other. They learnt about their rich cultural differences, their complementary graphic styles, and a 7-hour timezone difference. What they did have in common was each had two kids about the same age (one a pair of girls, the other boys).

Every kid was born a builder; every kid likes to sit in nature. It’s their way of discovering the world and dreaming of their future accomplishments. While they marvel at the heights of the cities and monuments they construct out of stacks of cubes, parents marvel at their ability to elaborate an unlimited range of worlds out of a limited range of materials. 

This project celebrates the humble and versatile cube. A deceptively simple yet powerful object of play and learning, regardless of age, whether you’re stacking them up in a sandbox, or learning 3D graphics for the first time. 

This project is dedicated to kids, those who were once children, to the dreamers and builders who still enjoy playing with cubes.

Coded in Vanilla JS, the project combines Yazid's iconic “Hashed/Hatched” aesthetic incorporated into childhood wooden toy block structures, and Zancan's signature lush foliage and framework, which enables all iterations to be plottable.
 
Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to get a SVG file suited for plotters
- Click on the image to download a 4K resolution PNG

metadata.name: Frequência #238
metadata.description:
Frequência is a 3D interactive installation, each object can be seen as a 2D drawing from multiple perspectives or as an animated object in 3D. It is a continuation of the concepts I explored in my works "Harmonium" and "Polyptych".

Available in multiple color schemes and different synthesis modes.

Instructions:

- use the mouse to navigate (zoom, pan and drag)
- press 'c' to switch between multiple camera angles
- press 'b' to pause the animation
- press 'p' to download the current view it in a custom resolution (always 3:4 ratio). Note that taking a screenshot will only work when seeing the piece live (click 'Open live' on fxhash), not on the mint page because of the sandboxed iframe of fxhash.

Berlin, December 2021
@bgola

metadata.name: CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE #470
metadata.description:
1 of 5 in CENTURY-XXX, Series 2
Edition of 1000

Tribute to Herbert W. Franke
“In Honor of the Dinosaur of Computer Art” 

Herbert W. Franke, a pioneer of computer art, passed away on July 16, 2022 at the age of 95. CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE is an homage to Franke’s MONDRIAN software developed for the Texas Instruments TI 99/4 home computer in 1979, and it’s a fundraiser to digitize his archive:

“Our goal is to raise 20,000 Euro so that ZKM Karlsruhe can digitize Herbert W. Franke’s 1,800 manuscripts and make them publicly available. If we raise more money, it will be donated to the Rütgers Foundation which supports children and young adults in Africa so that they can get access to and work with technology.” 

Each frame, a single “pixel” is added to the CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE image. When the software first loads, 100,000 frames are run in the background to start things off. Keep it running for hours or days to see it transform entirely — it’s an “infinite animation.”
